# Error Handling

## Rules

- **Always wrap async operations in try/catch.** Every `await` call or Promise chain must be inside a try/catch block. Never let async errors go unhandled.
- **Use typed errors from `@/shared/utils/errors`.** The project defines custom error classes (e.g., `AppError`, `ApiError`, `ValidationError`). Always throw and catch these typed errors instead of generic `Error` objects.
- **Report errors to Sentry via `@/modules/sentry`.** Import `captureAppError` for typed errors and `captureException` for unknown/raw errors. Never call Sentry SDK directly.
- **Show user-facing errors via toast notifications.** Use the `toast` utility (from sonner or similar) to display error messages to users. Always use i18n translation keys for toast messages.
- **Never swallow errors silently.** Every catch block must either report the error (Sentry), show a user-facing message (toast), or explicitly re-throw. An empty catch block is never acceptable.
- **Type the error as `unknown` in catch blocks.** TypeScript catch blocks receive `unknown`. Narrow the type before accessing error properties.
- **Use error boundaries for component-level errors.** Wrap route-level components and critical UI sections in React error boundaries that report to Sentry.

## Examples

### Good

```typescript
import { AppError, ApiError } from '@/shared/utils/errors';
import { captureAppError, captureException } from '@/modules/sentry';
import { toast } from 'sonner';

/**
 * Handles user deletion with proper error handling.
 */
const handleDeleteUser = async (userId: string) => {
  try {
    await deleteUser(userId);
    toast.success(t('users.delete_success'));
  } catch (error: unknown) {
    if (error instanceof ApiError) {
      captureAppError(error);
      if (error.status === 403) {
        toast.error(t('errors.forbidden'));
      } else if (error.status === 404) {
        toast.error(t('errors.not_found'));
      } else {
        toast.error(t('errors.generic'));
      }
    } else if (error instanceof AppError) {
      captureAppError(error);
      toast.error(t(`errors.${error.code}`));
    } else {
      captureException(error);
      toast.error(t('errors.unexpected'));
    }
  }
};

// React Query error handling in onError
const { mutate } = useDeleteUser({
  onError: (error: unknown) => {
    if (error instanceof ApiError) {
      captureAppError(error);
      toast.error(t('users.delete_failed'));
    } else {
      captureException(error);
      toast.error(t('errors.unexpected'));
    }
  },
});
```

### Bad

```typescript
// No try/catch on async
const handleDelete = async (id: string) => {
  await deleteUser(id); // Unhandled rejection if this fails
};

// Empty catch block (swallowing errors)
try {
  await fetchData();
} catch (e) {
  // silently ignored
}

// Using generic Error instead of typed errors
throw new Error('Something went wrong');

// Accessing error properties without type narrowing
catch (error) {
  console.error(error.message); // error is unknown, .message is unsafe
}

// Hardcoded English in toast
catch (error) {
  toast.error('Failed to delete user'); // Must use i18n
}

// console.error instead of Sentry
catch (error) {
  console.error('API failed:', error); // Use Sentry, not console
}

// Calling Sentry SDK directly
import * as Sentry from '@sentry/react';
Sentry.captureException(error); // Use @/modules/sentry wrapper
```
